text:
- Overview of memory hierarchy concepts, including cache memory, DRAM, SRAM, and main memory levels
- Principle of locality, encompassing temporal locality and spatial locality in data access patterns
- Definitions of cache hit, cache miss, block unit, hit ratio, miss penalty, and upper/lower memory levels
- Introduction to how memory hierarchies create the illusion of large, fast memory to bridge the CPU and slower main memory

- Types of cache organizations: direct mapped cache, set associative cache (n-way), and fully associative cache structures
- Address subdivision techniques, use of tags, valid bits, and block mapping in cache memory (indexing, tag comparison)
- Cache replacement policies, including least recently used (LRU), random replacement, and policy implications for different cache organizations
- Write policies for cache memory: write-through, write-back, write buffer, and write allocation strategies

- Metrics for measuring cache performance: hit time, miss penalty, memory stall cycles, and impact on CPU cycles per instruction (CPI)
- Calculation of memory stall cycles, miss rates, and miss penalties through example scenarios and formulas
- Multilevel cache hierarchy considerations, including L1 and L2 cache roles, block size effects, and global miss rates
- Tradeoffs and design decisions to optimize cache performance: increased associativity, block size changes, adding cache levels, and impact on system throughput

- MIPS instruction formats (R-type, I-type, J-type) and instruction execution flow: fetch, decode, execute, memory access, and write-back stages
- Single-cycle datapath structure, use of multiplexers, register file operations, and state elements (combinational vs. sequential circuits)
- Pipelined datapath stages (IF, ID, EX, MEM, WB), pipeline registers, pipelined control unit, and control signal generation (RegDst, ALUSrc, MemtoReg, RegWrite, MemRead, MemWrite, Branch, ALUOp)
- Pipeline hazards (structural, data, control), techniques for handling hazards: forwarding/bypassing, pipeline stalls, instruction scheduling, branch prediction (static/dynamic, 1-bit/2-bit predictors), and exception/interrupt handling in the pipeline
